THE HEAVENS IN MAY

T HE Constellation Vehiculum mo - vendi (the Moving Van ) is on the meridian the 1st of this month. The great three-ringed star Circus is now plainly visible in the evening sky. The stars of the first magnitude composing the Constellations Opera, which showed at their brightest during the winter months and were only partially visible during April, are now completely resolved in the brilliant nebula Europa.

On the last day of this month the planet Oyster sets, and is not again visible until September.

Venus will now approach Neptune and become obscured in the Surf nebula, the spectrum showing instead of pink a deep golden-brown indicating the presence of solar Tan.

THE HEAVENS IN SEPTEMBER

T HE minor clusters of the Constella¬ tion Exodus are again visible about this time to the West of the nebula Europa.

The planet Oyster also, which has been missing from the summer heavens since the end of April, is again to be seen.

An extensive and hazy nebula known as the Indian is a beautiful feature of the Sep¬ tember heaven, and when at its brightest is an indication of a return of warm weather.

Toward the end of this month a few of the brightest stars of the Thespian cluster of the Constellation Exodus begin to ap¬ pear, but as yet too dim to be seen even with an opera-glass.

THE HEAVENS IN DECEMBER

T OWARD the middle of December, Virgo (the Shopper ) will be on the meridian.

The Bowl Star which has been gaining in intensity for the past two months is now almost at the full. It is seen to be sur¬ rounded by a nebulous ring or halo, known as the Wreath or Holly nebula.

In this is a stellar nucleus called Santa , which increases in brightness until the 25th of the month, after which it disappears.

The Constellation Broadway (the Silky Way ) will be at its brightest, with stars of every magnumtude, and Venus as the Evening Star.
